WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.120
[Amit Varma]: Too many of us think of the world in terms of binaries. That makes it easy to make sense

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:17.400
[Amit Varma]: of the world. The most common binary is that of good and evil. That's why mainstream commercial

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:23.280
[Amit Varma]: cinema has heroes who are good and villains who are bad. Keep it simple for the audiences.

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:28.120
[Amit Varma]: Make it easy to root for one side over the other. That's why there are so few nuanced

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:34.020
[Amit Varma]: gods in religion. And even in our politics, in an age where so much has become so tribal,

00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:40.640
[Amit Varma]: we think in binaries. It's an easy way to make sense of a complex world. In these pandemic

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:46.600
[Amit Varma]: times, one binary that is all around us is that of the lockdown. So much of the discourse

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:52.120
[Amit Varma]: behaves as if there are two possible ways to act. One, have a lockdown. Two, have no

00:00:52.120 --> 00:00:57.320
[Amit Varma]: lockdown. But the truth is that this is not a binary choice, but a continuum along which

00:00:57.320 --> 00:01:03.000
[Amit Varma]: many other options exist. The best option, in fact, might be one in which we don't have

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:08.360
[Amit Varma]: a complete lockdown, but nor do we let the pandemic get out of control. What are these

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:13.640
[Amit Varma]: gradations? How can they be calibrated? What kind of metrics do we need to determine how

00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:19.200
[Amit Varma]: much of a lockdown is needed? And what kind of data do we need to make good decisions?

00:01:19.200 --> 00:01:24.720
[Amit Varma]: Most importantly, given the nature of our politics, and given how incompetent and ill-equipped

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:30.960
[Amit Varma]: our governments are, can good ideas even be implemented in practice?

00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:38.920
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:45.400
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:50.600
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen. My last episode on COVID-19 was recorded in the middle

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:55.400
[Amit Varma]: of April with Shruti Rajgopalan. When I think of the time that has passed since then, it

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:59.760
[Amit Varma]: feels like it went by in the blink of an eye. When I think of all that has happened in that

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:05.160
[Amit Varma]: time, it feels like an eternity. There has been so much pain and suffering across the

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:10.240
[Amit Varma]: world, and especially across India, that I sometimes feel guilty to even be able to live

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:15.520
[Amit Varma]: a relatively normal life. There is so much to process about all that happened. Shruti

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:20.880
[Amit Varma]: and I spoke about how policymakers were faced with thankless choices at that time. No matter

00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:26.720
[Amit Varma]: what they did, countless lives would be lost, and that cost would be viscerally visible.

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:32.520
[Amit Varma]: It would be seen, while any counterfactual would be unseen. And there is no way to calculate

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:38.080
[Amit Varma]: all the costs of any action, even in hindsight. For example, we know that the lockdown has

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:44.220
[Amit Varma]: been a disaster. There have been massive humanitarian costs, especially among the poor. Not having

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:48.400
[Amit Varma]: a lockdown could also have been a disaster, as our healthcare systems could have been

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:53.600
[Amit Varma]: overwhelmed, and again, the poor would have suffered the most. And it's easy to say that

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:58.280
[Amit Varma]: hey, do a lockdown but implement it well so suffering is minimal. But while that sounds

00:02:58.280 --> 00:03:04.780
[Amit Varma]: good on paper, given how poor our state capacity is, that might have been utopian to aim for.

00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:09.840
[Amit Varma]: In fact, as I argued in a column a few weeks ago, what India may have learned from this

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:15.960
[Amit Varma]: is that our flailing state is a bigger disaster than COVID-19. That earlier episode and the

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:20.900
[Amit Varma]: column will be linked from the show notes. Today's episode, though, doesn't focus only

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:26.860
[Amit Varma]: on what has happened in the last few weeks, but also on what we can do moving forward.

00:03:26.860 --> 00:03:32.400
[Amit Varma]: My guest is Anoop Malani, a polymath public intellectual based in Chicago, who has a degree

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:37.840
[Amit Varma]: in law, a PhD in economics, and has worked closely in health economics over the last

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:43.440
[Amit Varma]: decade and a half. He has written papers on past pandemics, the insights from which inform

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:48.920
[Amit Varma]: many of his thoughts on the current one. And he's not a believer in pontificating from

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:54.280
[Amit Varma]: a distance. For years, he has been advising governments and working closely with them

00:03:54.280 --> 00:03:59.560
[Amit Varma]: to bring about actual change on the ground. And in the case of COVID-19 as well, Anoop

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:05.120
[Amit Varma]: has put forward a plan for coming out of lockdown that aims to minimize death and suffering.

00:04:05.120 --> 00:04:11.080
[Amit Varma]: It's a nuanced plan based around what he calls adaptive controls. It takes a position that

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:17.060
[Amit Varma]: both removing the lockdown completely and keeping it going as is are impractical solutions

00:04:17.060 --> 00:04:22.800
[Amit Varma]: with huge costs. Instead, we need to have an approach by which we lift controls to varying

00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:28.440
[Amit Varma]: degrees depending on local conditions, and we keep adapting to new data. He elaborates

00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:33.800
[Amit Varma]: upon this in this conversation. And he also shares his larger thoughts on what the state

00:04:33.800 --> 00:04:38.440
[Amit Varma]: and society can learn from this pandemic. We spend the first 40 minutes of a conversation

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:43.840
[Amit Varma]: exploring his personal evolution as a thinker, which I found fascinating. And we start talking

00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:49.840
[Amit Varma]: about COVID-19 after the break around the 40 minute mark. Before we begin this conversation,

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:55.680
[Amit Varma]: though, let's take a quick commercial break. If you enjoy listening to the scene and the

00:04:55.680 --> 00:05:00.560
[Amit Varma]: unseen, you can play a part in keeping the show alive. The scene and the unseen has been

