[Amit Varma]: on all podcast apps and at seen unseen.in. This is just a gesture of appreciation. Help

00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:10.920
[Amit Varma]: keep the scene going. seen unseen.in slash support.

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:16.880
[Amit Varma]: Anoop, welcome to the scene and the unseen. Thank you. Happy to be here. So Anoop, you

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:21.440
[Amit Varma]: know, before we get to the subject at hand, which is the pandemic and the lockdown and

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:26.000
[Amit Varma]: the difficult few months that we've been having, tell me a little bit about your background,

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.760
[Amit Varma]: because I was sort of looking at your background and your CV and all of that. And it seemed

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:34.240
[Amit Varma]: to me that you're like the Forrest Gump of academics, you did a law degree, you clerked

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:40.480
[Amit Varma]: in the Supreme Court in the US, you did an econ PhD. And, you know, you've also written

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:45.880
[Amit Varma]: a lot of papers on medical and healthcare issues. So where did it all start? Where did

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:48.560
[Amit Varma]: the journey begin? What did you want to do when you were a kid?

00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:54.000
[Guest]: Yeah, that's a great question. I do feel a little bit like the Forrest Gump of academics

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.980
[Guest]: and also the real world, doing all those different things actually puts you in interesting places

00:06:57.980 --> 00:07:03.640
[Guest]: at different times. So I got a chance to see, for example, 9-11 up close. But let's see,

00:07:03.640 --> 00:07:07.200
[Guest]: I think it probably started in high school, you know, typical Indian immigrant kid, parents

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:12.160
[Guest]: wanted me to be a doctor. And, you know, I think I probably wanted to satisfy my parents,

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:17.880
[Guest]: but my parents have very high standards. So, you know, again, classic situation. In seventh

00:07:17.880 --> 00:07:24.800
[Guest]: or eighth grade, I did a science fair project where I tried to see the impact of radiation

00:07:24.800 --> 00:07:30.000
[Guest]: on mice. So this was back in the 1980s. There was still a real concern about nuclear war.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.840
[Guest]: And so I thought it'd be interesting to x-ray mice to see what the impact of radiation would

00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:40.200
[Guest]: be on health. And so mice weren't easy to work with. My dad was a doctor, so was my

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:45.560
[Guest]: mom, but my dad was a doctor. And he said he would figure out a way for me to irradiate

00:07:45.560 --> 00:07:50.160
[Guest]: the mice at his hospital, the hospital that he had privileges at. And so we went and we

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:55.600
[Guest]: irradiated the mice. And then I tracked the mice for, I don't know, I guess weeks just

00:07:55.600 --> 00:08:01.000
[Guest]: to see what their IgG levels were over time. And I think my parents were super excited

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.680
[Guest]: because they thought that I was interested in medicine. And what I realized back then

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:09.280
[Guest]: was that I was actually interested in the research component of it. And so that science

00:08:09.280 --> 00:08:15.120
[Guest]: experiment went well, more for me than the mice. And then I decided that I would be a

00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:21.680
[Guest]: little bit interested in research. In high school, I decided I would debate. And I don't

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:26.840
[Guest]: know if you've ever debated, but debate is basically about making, not just learning

00:08:26.840 --> 00:08:31.360
[Guest]: how to make arguments, but making other people's arguments and leveraging those arguments in

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:36.440
[Guest]: order to win a debate. And what I always thought during this process was, why am I only repeating

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:40.400
[Guest]: what other people's arguments are? Wouldn't it be more interesting if I could make those

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:45.640
[Guest]: arguments myself? That is to say, do the research that would help other people make arguments.

00:08:45.640 --> 00:08:50.360
[Guest]: And so I think those are the two things I had going off to college. The other thing

00:08:50.360 --> 00:08:55.540
[Guest]: I had was, you know, in high school, my form of rebellion wasn't to cut my hair in strange

00:08:55.540 --> 00:09:00.280
[Guest]: ways or to, you know, wear crazy clothes. My rebellion was to decide not to become a

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:06.680
[Guest]: doctor, which, you know, in a family constitutes rebellion, which is not to say I wasn't going

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:10.360
[Guest]: to go to college. It was just I was going to do something other than medicine. So when

00:09:10.360 --> 00:09:15.960
[Guest]: I went off, went to college, I initially majored in political science, mainly because that

00:09:15.960 --> 00:09:22.880
[Guest]: seemed to flow naturally from the debate activities I was doing in high school. And then in college,

00:09:22.880 --> 00:09:30.520
[Guest]: I got to take some math courses, and I realized I enjoyed math a lot more than political science.

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:35.640
[Guest]: And so while my major was political science, it's really just math classes I took for my

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:40.000
[Guest]: last two years, mainly at least. That's my main memory is the math classes. I remember

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:43.200
[Guest]: almost nothing about my political science classes.

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:49.480
[Guest]: And sometime around my fourth year, I must have been in my third year. So I was at Georgetown

00:09:49.480 --> 00:09:53.760
[Guest]: University in Washington, D.C., and there's a famous bookstore called Kramer's Books in

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:59.000
[Guest]: DuPont Circle. And I would go there with some frequency and just kind of hang out. And they

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.720
[Guest]: also had a coffee shop. So back in the day, so in the 1990s, that was still relatively

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:08.720
[Guest]: novel. I would go and, you know, have a coffee, read books. And I happened upon a book by

00:10:08.720 --> 00:10:13.520
[Guest]: Gary Becker. I think it's called The Economic Approach to Human Behavior.

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:20.040
[Guest]: And I, for some time, because of debate, just being curious, you know, tried to understand

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:24.360
[Guest]: how humans behave. Just, you know, I think everybody does this, try to figure out what

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:28.800
[Guest]: the world, how it functions so that they can figure out their role in it and how to interact

00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:32.080
[Guest]: with it. And so I was doing the same thing, except, you know, I had a little bit of math

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:37.320
[Guest]: in my pocket. And so I, you know, was always trying to figure out how everything fit together,

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:41.800
[Guest]: you know, why I was attracted to the concept of democracy or, you know, what this notion

00:10:41.800 --> 00:10:46.080
[Guest]: of this thing called rights is and how it made sense and how, what role should the government

00:10:46.080 --> 00:10:48.680
[Guest]: play, you know, just kind of standard stuff that a political scientist would think about,

00:10:48.680 --> 00:10:53.400
[Guest]: but from a mathematical perspective. And I can never really get it all organized in my

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:58.320
[Guest]: head. I had intuitions, but not a structure. And all of a sudden I happened upon this book

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:04.120
[Guest]: and it's an amazing book. And for the first time, I realized that people have been thinking

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:08.680
[Guest]: in a similar way. I remember I wasn't an economics major. I was a political science major. I

00:11:08.680 --> 00:11:13.520
[Guest]: wasn't reading Chicago economics at the time, certainly not Becker. And so this is the first

00:11:13.520 --> 00:11:16.280
[Guest]: time I had an eye-opening experience where I said, look, this person is thinking the

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:22.320
[Guest]: way that I want to think using the tools that I'd like to be able to use. And really I want

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:27.520
[Guest]: to study with this person or, you know, do similar sorts of stuff. So then I decided

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:31.800
[Guest]: to apply to grad school in economics. Now I had a political science background, but

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:36.200
[Guest]: I'd taken a lot of math classes and had some chances. So that was one decision I made.

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:40.960
[Guest]: I was going to apply to economics grad school. The other thing is that I was at Georgetown.

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:45.520
[Guest]: And if I remember correctly, my class, something like, I was in this program called the School

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:49.120
[Guest]: of Foreign Service. It wasn't the right best fit for me, but it was a program that I was

00:11:49.120 --> 00:11:55.560
[Guest]: in where you studied, your focus was international more than, say, domestic. And my recollection

00:11:55.560 --> 00:11:59.360
[Guest]: was something like 50 or 75% of students applied to law school. I'm not saying all of them

00:11:59.360 --> 00:12:05.800
[Guest]: went to law school, but 75% I heard had applied to law school. So, you know, I'm a young kid,

00:12:05.800 --> 00:12:09.940
[Guest]: so I'm going to do what the crowd does too. So I decided I would also apply to law schools.

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:13.640
[Guest]: So I applied to law schools and economics grad schools. And the only place that I got

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:18.960
[Guest]: into both was the University of Chicago. So that's how I got to the University of Chicago.

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:22.200
[Guest]: And so you know the background there. At the University of Chicago, the very first class

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:27.200
[Guest]: you take in the economics department is with Gary Becker. Well, the first microeconomics

00:12:27.200 --> 00:12:32.120
[Guest]: classes. So this is fantastic for me. This is exactly what I'd hoped for. I felt so lucky

00:12:32.120 --> 00:12:38.160
[Guest]: that I had this opportunity. Around this time, I also met a person named Jim Heckman. So

00:12:38.160 --> 00:12:44.560
[Guest]: Jim Heckman was teaching, I think he taught the second quarter econometrics course. And

00:12:44.560 --> 00:12:50.440
[Guest]: I didn't have an interest in statistics before grad school. And then I met Jim Heckman. And

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:57.360
[Guest]: Jim, you know, kind of introduces you to the idea of causal inference, which is to say,

00:12:57.360 --> 00:13:02.840
[Guest]: you know, if you say X causes Y, in order to say that, you have to say if there was

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:09.320
[Guest]: not X, you would not necessarily or you have less probability of getting outcome Y. And

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:13.320
[Guest]: how do you think very formally about that kind of statement? And so he introduced something

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:17.000
[Guest]: called a potential outcomes framework, which I thought was fascinating. Obviously, he'd

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.400
[Guest]: been, you know, had seminal work in the late 1970s that introduced this concept, kind of

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:27.160
[Guest]: in parallel with Don Rubin. And so it was fantastic. And he and I hit it off. And so

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:33.440
[Guest]: the second year I was there, I think I was his TA for that course. And so there was those

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:37.840
[Guest]: were the two kind of big influences. We can talk about some of the other people I met

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:42.120
[Guest]: along the way, but but those are the two big influences that I had. And then Chicago is

00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:49.720
[Guest]: a very strange place. Chicago is, you know, I think everybody associates with market economics.

00:13:49.720 --> 00:13:54.360
[Guest]: And they take that approach very seriously in all aspects. So Chicago is also known as

00:13:54.360 --> 00:13:59.440
[Guest]: a place that provides very little support. So when you start out, you have to, even if

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:03.000
[Guest]: you're a third year student or fourth year student, you got to make it on your own. What

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:07.480
[Guest]: does that mean? That means you figure out what papers to write, you write them, and

00:14:07.480 --> 00:14:12.240
[Guest]: hopefully you're successful on the market, especially in the 1990s. There was no sense

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:16.560
[Guest]: that the graduate program was there to support you in your efforts on the market. Sure, you

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:21.080
[Guest]: can get a recommendation, but it was really incumbent upon you to come up with a paper,

00:14:21.080 --> 00:14:25.200
[Guest]: incumbent upon you to kind of get out there, you'll, you know, the thought was, if you're

00:14:25.200 --> 00:14:28.920
[Guest]: good, you don't really need a recommendation, your paper should do all the work for you.

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:34.320
[Guest]: And so I knew this during this time. And I was among a group of people that were quite

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:39.440
[Guest]: star, you know, that turned out to be stars. And while I did well, I was always worried

00:14:39.440 --> 00:14:43.000
[Guest]: that these people were going to, there are not that many academic jobs out there in top

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.560
[Guest]: places. And so I was always worried, you know, what was going to happen. So some of the names

00:14:46.560 --> 00:14:51.040
[Guest]: actually will be names that now many people will kind of appreciate. Yvonne Wernering,

00:14:51.040 --> 00:14:57.720
[Guest]: MIT, Ed Vitlasil, I think he's at Yale, Matthias Dabke, who's made quite an impact in macro

00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:02.240
[Guest]: and family economics, among others. And so I started worrying.

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:06.040
[Amit Varma]: I was actually very curious about the Gary Becker connection. Because you know, when

00:15:06.040 --> 00:15:10.720
[Amit Varma]: I read that he was one of your advisors, you know, while you were doing your econ PhD,

00:15:10.720 --> 00:15:15.680
[Amit Varma]: it struck me that he was, you know, almost the last intellectual of a certain kind, in

00:15:15.680 --> 00:15:20.760
[Amit Varma]: the sense that he straddled all these disciplines, you know, Milton Friedman called him, quote,

00:15:20.760 --> 00:15:24.400
[Amit Varma]: the greatest social scientist who has lived in work, but stop quote, and Justin Wolfers

00:15:24.400 --> 00:15:29.320
[Amit Varma]: called him the most important social scientist in the last 50 years. And it struck me that

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:36.200
[Amit Varma]: in that sense, he was almost like a 19th century intellectual, that he wasn't bound by a specialization,

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:41.480
[Amit Varma]: that he was, you know, delving into all these different disciplines, not just economics,

00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:46.560
[Amit Varma]: but also sociology, racial discrimination, crime, just a few days ago, I was reading

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:51.320
[Amit Varma]: his work on rational addiction. And it's just fascinating work. And it sort of comes from

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:56.040
[Amit Varma]: that classic impulse to try and understand human nature. And it seems to me that when

00:15:56.040 --> 00:16:00.840
[Amit Varma]: I look upon your arc, and your interest in the variety of things that you've done, was

00:16:00.840 --> 00:16:03.240
[Amit Varma]: he a direct influence in that sense,

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:08.200
[Guest]: it would be hard to understate how important Gary was, in the way we thought about the

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:14.400
[Guest]: world. So, you know, we had a set of tools, so some basic economic models, and some techniques,

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:19.040
[Guest]: some framework for the world. And we were taught to think about everything that way.

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:23.160
[Guest]: So, you know, for me, the first approach is to think about how judges behaved,

00:16:23.160 --> 00:16:27.880
[Guest]: which I'll explain in a second, because I eventually turned to law soon after where

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:34.000
[Guest]: I left off, but, you know, thought about how judges behaved, how people answered surveys,

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:39.560
[Guest]: how clinical trials functioned, almost everything I thought of, I thought through an economic

00:16:39.560 --> 00:16:44.600
[Guest]: lens. And the reason was, was Gary said that you should, and that it was fruitful to do

00:16:44.600 --> 00:16:48.320
[Guest]: so. And he demonstrated it in terms of, you know, you've mentioned crime, we could talk

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:53.600
[Guest]: family, we could talk addiction, we could talk advertising, you name the topic, and

00:16:53.600 --> 00:16:58.240
[Guest]: he's thought about it. And he wasn't alone, by the way, there was a foundation there,

00:16:58.240 --> 00:17:02.760
[Guest]: you know, before then, you had, you know, Milton Friedman talking about the draft, you

00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:07.760
[Guest]: know, obviously, then more classic subjects, but there's a wide range. So there's this

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:14.400
[Guest]: notion of, I mean, not in an aggressive way, but that economics should be hegemonic in

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:19.720
[Guest]: the sense that it should go to other fields, and try to introduce mathematical modeling.

00:17:19.720 --> 00:17:24.880
[Guest]: And now, you know, that's kind of, I think, back then, when I say back then, I mean, prior

00:17:24.880 --> 00:17:30.280
[Guest]: to the 1990s, I think that was extremely radical. And in some sections, it is still radical,

00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:35.620
[Guest]: but not really today. I mean, today, the idea that you would take applied math and apply

00:17:35.620 --> 00:17:41.360
[Guest]: it to every single topic doesn't seem surprising. And this epidemic slash pandemic that we're

00:17:41.360 --> 00:17:45.280
[Guest]: seeing now is a great example of this. If you think about epidemiology, there's the

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:50.540
[Guest]: non-technical shoe leather epidemiology of going to find the people that are infected

00:17:50.540 --> 00:17:55.260
[Guest]: and then addressing that. And then there's the applied math version of it, which is SIR

00:17:55.260 --> 00:18:00.040
[Guest]: and more complicated models. And we are perfectly comfortable with that now. And I think that

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:04.360
[Guest]: part of that is, you know, the idea that you can use applied math tools and a structure

00:18:04.360 --> 00:18:09.200
[Guest]: to address things. The only thing that economics really adds to that is to say, look, we shouldn't

00:18:09.200 --> 00:18:14.720
[Guest]: just use math for biology or physics or chemistry. We should use math for human behavior. And

00:18:14.720 --> 00:18:19.980
[Guest]: there's some simple ideas that can help you organize those mathematical theories to whatever

00:18:19.980 --> 00:18:24.440
[Guest]: interaction humans have. And I think the ultimate example of that actually is people applying

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:28.840
[Guest]: it also to animals and animal behavior, which is another situation where it's just like,

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:34.240
[Guest]: look, every sort of interaction you can see in the world, regardless of what's doing the

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:38.640
[Guest]: interaction, there's a value to using applied math and some basic underlying principles

00:18:38.640 --> 00:18:43.480
[Guest]: or axioms in order to organize that. And it's super helpful in terms of prediction, right?

00:18:43.480 --> 00:18:47.320
[Guest]: It's really hard for me to understand how people behave until I have a framework to

00:18:47.320 --> 00:18:50.480
[Guest]: think about it. And these tools that Gary had helped me think about that.

00:18:50.480 --> 00:18:54.520
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to law now. What was your experience there? Like, you know, you clerked for Sandra

00:18:54.520 --> 00:18:59.000
[Amit Varma]: Day O'Connor in the Supreme Court. And what was that journey like? What fascinated you

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:04.880
[Amit Varma]: about law? And were you sort of looking at the legal system through the tools of economics?

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:10.120
[Guest]: Yeah, so that was an interesting journey. So I think the initial interest in law was

00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:14.640
[Guest]: not merely, I kind of understated my interest in law. So I initially said that I was interested

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:17.920
[Guest]: mainly because everybody else at Georgetown was applying to law. That's not entirely correct.

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:22.040
[Guest]: If you, you know, debate in high school or college, you're going to think a lot about

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:25.920
[Guest]: politics. If you're a political science major, you're going to do it again. And a critical

00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:30.160
[Guest]: component of political science is the law. And so there was an underlying interest in

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:34.800
[Guest]: the law. You know, when I first went to University of Chicago, I did my economics PhD course

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:39.080
[Guest]: work first, and I started to lose interest in law because I found the economics so new

00:19:39.080 --> 00:19:44.840
[Guest]: and so fascinating. But while I was working with Jim Heckman, and not just as his TA,

00:19:44.840 --> 00:19:49.560
[Guest]: but as research assistant, he introduced me to a gentleman named Richard Posner. I'd never

00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:54.800
[Guest]: heard of Richard Posner before, which is probably more a sign of my lack of education than anything

00:19:54.800 --> 00:19:59.800
[Guest]: else. Dick Posner was, at that time, a judge, also a lecturer at the University of Chicago

00:19:59.800 --> 00:20:05.460
[Guest]: Law School, one of the founders of the law and economics movement, along with folks like

00:20:05.460 --> 00:20:10.880
[Guest]: Becker and Aaron Director, and Ronald Coase, who was also there at the time. And he and

00:20:10.880 --> 00:20:16.880
[Guest]: I hit it off. And we wanted to work together, either as RAs or as co-authors. But at the

00:20:16.880 --> 00:20:21.960
[Guest]: time, I was working for Jim Heckman. And Jim is notorious, both in terms of number of hours

00:20:21.960 --> 00:20:27.320
[Guest]: you have to work, but also in not allowing you to do anything other than his work. But

00:20:27.320 --> 00:20:32.840
[Guest]: he respected Dick Posner enough to let me switch jobs. So I went from an RA for Heckman

00:20:32.840 --> 00:20:39.500
[Guest]: to an RA for Dick Posner. And anybody that's had an interaction with Posner, and that's

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:45.040
[Guest]: Eric's father, will find him fascinating. He's like Becker. He is extremely prolific,

00:20:45.040 --> 00:20:48.880
[Guest]: likes to think about everything, and is very systematic in thinking about lots of things.

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:52.760
[Guest]: I think a little bit more than Becker, he's willing to deviate from standard economic

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:57.760
[Guest]: models, especially as his career evolved. So it was very interesting to see that. And

00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:01.880
[Guest]: I ended up being the kind of person that was defending the classic economic models, because

00:21:01.880 --> 00:21:05.360
[Guest]: I was just a young student in economics at the time. And he was willing to push them

00:21:05.360 --> 00:21:10.640
[Guest]: a little bit more. So we had some interactions. He convinced me to kind of resume my law education.

00:21:10.640 --> 00:21:16.800
[Guest]: So I turned to law school. And one thing I discovered was that law school is very hard,

00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:21.200
[Guest]: but it's not nearly as hard as economics graduate school. This is going to tie back into the

00:21:21.200 --> 00:21:25.280
[Guest]: Supreme Court in just a second. I found, I didn't tell a lot of people at this time,

00:21:25.280 --> 00:21:30.920
[Guest]: but I found law to be a relief from economics in terms of how much less work it required

00:21:30.920 --> 00:21:36.240
[Guest]: to succeed. It was hard nonetheless, but it just was much easier. And that showed in my

00:21:36.240 --> 00:21:40.320
[Guest]: grades in economics grad school were fine, but my grades in law school were a little

00:21:40.320 --> 00:21:45.360
[Guest]: bit better as a result of the change in intensity, which I found to be a little bit of a relief,

00:21:45.360 --> 00:21:51.480
[Guest]: too. So that performance and my rapport that I had with some of the professors that I'd

00:21:51.480 --> 00:21:57.920
[Guest]: met indirectly, so Dick Posner and Richard Epstein and some of the others, allowed me

00:21:57.920 --> 00:22:03.240
[Guest]: to do well enough in law school to apply for clerkships. And I was able to secure a Supreme

00:22:03.240 --> 00:22:06.760
[Guest]: Court clerkship. It's very interesting. You get these clerkships ahead of time. So I knew

00:22:06.760 --> 00:22:12.780
[Guest]: by my third year that two years after graduation, I would be clerking for Justice O'Connor.

00:22:12.780 --> 00:22:17.240
[Guest]: In the interim, I was going to clerk for a person, a good friend named Stephen Williams,

00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:22.760
[Guest]: who on the DC circuit in Washington, one of the main appellate courts. So that's how I

00:22:22.760 --> 00:22:28.480
[Guest]: got the opportunity to clerk with Justice O'Connor. And that was an eye-opening experience

00:22:28.480 --> 00:22:35.800
[Guest]: in the sense that it is the first time that I went from just writing papers that maybe

00:22:35.800 --> 00:22:39.720
[Guest]: people would read or being an RA, in which case somebody else is writing the papers and

00:22:39.720 --> 00:22:45.000
[Guest]: I was doing stuff in the background, to actually writing... It's actually the second year that

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:50.380
[Guest]: I was writing things of consequence. I would undersell it if I said I didn't have the same

00:22:50.380 --> 00:22:55.680
[Guest]: experience my first year clerking at the DC circuit for Stephen Williams. That year, the

00:22:55.680 --> 00:23:00.000
[Guest]: year that I clerked for Stephen Williams, we had the Microsoft case. So this was the

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:06.400
[Guest]: big antitrust case in the year 2000 that showed up before the DC circuit. And there, I had

00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:11.840
[Guest]: my first big practical introduction to antitrust and got to learn a little bit about the tech

00:23:11.840 --> 00:23:17.300
[Guest]: industry, which had just had a crash or was in the midst of a crash. So that was my first

00:23:17.300 --> 00:23:20.920
[Guest]: opportunity to do something of direct importance. But then, you know, there's always a layer

00:23:20.920 --> 00:23:25.440
[Guest]: above the appellate court that was the Supreme Court that made the ultimate decisions aside

00:23:25.440 --> 00:23:30.120
[Guest]: from say Congress and the president that would make these decisions. And so that was my first

00:23:30.120 --> 00:23:36.560
[Guest]: chance to see that in action. And also to see the process, not just, you know, kind

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:41.640
[Guest]: of help make decisions, but see the process. And so I found that very insightful.

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:46.800
[Amit Varma]: And were you thinking about a career in law at any point? Or in fact, to sort of rephrase

00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:51.720
[Amit Varma]: that question, were you, as a person, were you driven by a sense of what you want to

00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:57.960
[Amit Varma]: be like, I want to be X or Y or Z? Or were you more driven by problems that interested

00:23:57.960 --> 00:24:02.600
[Amit Varma]: you that I want to solve this problem? For example, it was a you know, a problem that

00:24:02.600 --> 00:24:07.520
[Amit Varma]: drove you to do your little test on mice when you were a kid. So were you driven more by

00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:11.560
[Amit Varma]: problems? Or was there a sense of I want this to be my career? And I want this to be my

00:24:11.560 --> 00:24:15.640
[Amit Varma]: path? How did you approach all of that? Because you left the law soon enough, and you kind

00:24:15.640 --> 00:24:19.000
[Amit Varma]: of got back into, you know, academics and economics.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:24.720
[Guest]: I don't think I had a grand ambition to be anything in particular. I've noticed two things.

00:24:24.720 --> 00:24:29.000
[Guest]: One is I like shiny new objects. So if you present me with a new problem or a new thing

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:34.040
[Guest]: to think about, I'm always attracted and want to think about it. And probably have too much

00:24:34.040 --> 00:24:38.280
[Guest]: of a tendency to drop what it is that I'm working on to think about that new, look at

00:24:38.280 --> 00:24:42.480
[Guest]: that new shiny object and think about that new, new, interesting idea that you've got.

00:24:42.480 --> 00:24:49.040
[Guest]: The second thing I guess I had a sense of is trying to organize my way of thinking about

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:52.000
[Guest]: the world, which is to say not only do I want to think about your new object, but I want

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.760
[Guest]: to figure out how that relates to everything else that I've been thinking about. It's not

00:24:55.760 --> 00:25:01.160
[Guest]: like I have some notebook with a grand theory of the world, but I feel this strong sense

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:05.760
[Guest]: of trying to make things consistent and rethink some of the old stuff in light of what I'm

00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:10.000
[Guest]: learning about new stuff. And so that was part of it. That sense of wanting to understand

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:13.840
[Guest]: the world, I think, is what probably led me to academics. You know, I don't want to undersell

00:25:13.840 --> 00:25:18.640
[Guest]: the idea that going to a school where people judged you by whether or not you became an

00:25:18.640 --> 00:25:22.560
[Guest]: academic in particular. University of Chicago was really bad because the standard was not

00:25:22.560 --> 00:25:25.480
[Guest]: only are you going to become an academic, but are you going to win the Nobel Prize?

00:25:25.480 --> 00:25:30.480
[Guest]: You know, that kind of pushed you towards academics too. So I did think about law, and

00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:34.480
[Guest]: I thought about law because along the way, when you go to law school, it's very practical.

00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:39.080
[Guest]: You know, you have to spend your summers, and I spent one summer only doing this, which

00:25:39.080 --> 00:25:43.960
[Guest]: is working at a law firm. And I worked at two firms, and both of them were fantastic.

00:25:43.960 --> 00:25:48.560
[Guest]: I realized, I saw for the first time that outside of academia, there are some people

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:53.400
[Guest]: doing some very important things and that are incredibly smart. So I worked for a firm

00:25:53.400 --> 00:25:57.760
[Guest]: called Wachtell Lipton, Rosen and Katz in New York, which is one of the premier M&A

00:25:57.760 --> 00:26:02.920
[Guest]: firms, among other things in New York, and just met spectacularly smart people who were

00:26:02.920 --> 00:26:08.040
[Guest]: intellectually curious, but at the same time were very practical. They were resolving matters,

00:26:08.040 --> 00:26:13.160
[Guest]: both in court and M&A deals, for example. And then I went to a place called Kellogg

00:26:13.160 --> 00:26:17.440
[Guest]: Huber Hanson Todd, I think that's what it was called back then. It might just be Kellogg

00:26:17.440 --> 00:26:22.720
[Guest]: Huber now, in Washington, DC. And again, same experience, just really bright people. And

00:26:22.720 --> 00:26:27.760
[Guest]: I met a gentleman named Peter Huber, and he was one of the founders of the firm. And he

00:26:27.760 --> 00:26:32.880
[Guest]: actually was found very interesting because he both continued to write books and had a

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:37.880
[Guest]: practical consulting firm slash law firm. And so that's when I first entertained the

00:26:37.880 --> 00:26:43.520
[Guest]: idea of being a lawyer. There's one other per name I should mention is Ken Feinberg

00:26:43.520 --> 00:26:49.600
[Guest]: is a person that I met who had his own firm in DC and he played a really interesting role.

00:26:49.600 --> 00:26:54.320
[Guest]: He helped serve as kind of a private judge to resolve matters. So when you had like the

00:26:54.320 --> 00:27:00.560
[Guest]: Agent Orange Victims Fund, or I think he might have done the 9-11 Fund, he was the one that

00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:04.880
[Guest]: would allocate money from the fund to different claimants. So that was also very interesting

00:27:04.880 --> 00:27:09.320
[Guest]: because he was also very intellectual about it and thinking about how do we not just figure

00:27:09.320 --> 00:27:13.160
[Guest]: out who was harmed, but practically how you allocate a limit out of resources across these

00:27:13.160 --> 00:27:18.600
[Guest]: people and account for proof. So I think that that really kind of got me thinking that maybe

00:27:18.600 --> 00:27:23.680
[Guest]: law is a real career. And I think I probably ended up in a law school first for two reasons.

00:27:23.680 --> 00:27:28.160
[Guest]: One was because it was a nice compromise between the two. It allowed me to see and respect

00:27:28.160 --> 00:27:33.580
[Guest]: these individuals who were actually making, you know, kind of intellectual contributions

00:27:33.580 --> 00:27:39.360
[Guest]: in a practical way in cases or in transactional matters, and at the same time keep a foothold

00:27:39.360 --> 00:27:43.640
[Guest]: in academics. And one thing that people don't appreciate about law schools, especially modern

00:27:43.640 --> 00:27:49.800
[Guest]: law schools, and maybe this is more so about kind of top-tier law schools, unfortunately,

00:27:49.800 --> 00:27:55.560
[Guest]: is that they allowed you to think academically about a broad range of subjects. So you're

00:27:55.560 --> 00:28:00.280
[Guest]: supposed to think about law, but they didn't penalize you if you thought about non-law

00:28:00.280 --> 00:28:06.800
[Guest]: topics. And so that was the other thing that I think led me back to, you know, law, and

00:28:06.800 --> 00:28:10.560
[Guest]: in particular legal academia, at least to start my career. I think that answers your

00:28:10.560 --> 00:28:11.560
[Amit Varma]: question.

00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:14.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And it's interesting that you should describe the very smart people you met in

00:28:14.600 --> 00:28:19.560
[Amit Varma]: these law firms as intellectually curious and very practical, because that also sort

00:28:19.560 --> 00:28:23.720
[Amit Varma]: of describes a lot of the, seems to describe to me at least a lot of the work that you

00:28:23.720 --> 00:28:29.160
[Amit Varma]: went on to do specifically in health economics, you know, which kind of almost puts you, you

00:28:29.160 --> 00:28:33.440
[Amit Varma]: know, a decade and a half before COVID, it's almost like you were on a trajectory to bring

00:28:33.440 --> 00:28:38.160
[Amit Varma]: you where we are today. So what were the sort of problems that, the shiny new things as

00:28:38.160 --> 00:28:41.640
[Amit Varma]: it were, that drew you towards health economics?

00:28:41.640 --> 00:28:47.120
[Guest]: So again, you know, it's going to be individuals to start with. So just around the time Jim

00:28:47.120 --> 00:28:52.040
[Guest]: Heckman had introduced me to Dick Posner, I started thinking about how judges behave.

00:28:52.040 --> 00:28:57.200
[Guest]: I also met this person named Tom Philipson, who's actually an important person in the

00:28:57.200 --> 00:29:00.680
[Guest]: current context, because I think he's the head of the CEA, Council of Economic Advisors

00:29:00.680 --> 00:29:05.240
[Guest]: for the U.S. President. And he was a health economist and had some really interesting

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:11.480
[Guest]: ideas. One of these ideas was that you could use economics to understand how people behave

00:29:11.480 --> 00:29:17.240
[Guest]: during epidemics and how you can use economics to understand how people make decisions about

00:29:17.240 --> 00:29:19.440
[Guest]: treatment for disease.

00:29:19.440 --> 00:29:23.080
[Guest]: So I began having conversations with him and he was, you know, he'd begun thinking about

00:29:23.080 --> 00:29:26.840
[Guest]: this in the mid 1990s. So he'd already kind of had a head start in thinking about this,

00:29:26.840 --> 00:29:30.920
[Guest]: but I thought it was fascinating. And so we talked about that, but the one idea that I

00:29:30.920 --> 00:29:37.840
[Guest]: latched onto that led me to kind of embrace working with Thomas a bit more was that he

00:29:37.840 --> 00:29:43.960
[Guest]: viewed, he had this concept called a data market. And the basic idea is that when you

00:29:43.960 --> 00:29:48.080
[Guest]: do a survey, for example, for research, you want to do a survey to see who people are

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:51.600
[Guest]: going to vote for. You want to do a survey to see what income people have. You want to

00:29:51.600 --> 00:29:56.920
[Guest]: do a survey to see, you know, how has COVID affected them. You have to think of it as

00:29:56.920 --> 00:30:02.040
[Guest]: a labor market, or at least as a market where the respondents are supplying information

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:07.160
[Guest]: and the surveyors are demanding that information. And there's some trade and you have to think

00:30:07.160 --> 00:30:11.320
[Guest]: about what the price of that trade is and what the quality of the supply is here at

00:30:11.320 --> 00:30:12.320
[Guest]: information.

00:30:12.320 --> 00:30:17.460
[Guest]: And so that really started influencing me, made me think a lot differently or think very

00:30:17.460 --> 00:30:21.320
[Guest]: differently about econometrics. Econometrics, we kind of took the data as given. We had

00:30:21.320 --> 00:30:26.520
[Guest]: some discussion of selection obviously with Jim Heckman, but it made me think a little

00:30:26.520 --> 00:30:32.400
[Guest]: bit more about whether or not we could use the idea of a market to improve statistical

00:30:32.400 --> 00:30:39.120
[Guest]: inference from surveys. And so he and I wrote a paper together in 1999 about these and the

00:30:39.120 --> 00:30:43.040
[Guest]: role that incentives play and how that changes the inferences that you'd make.

00:30:43.040 --> 00:30:47.520
[Guest]: But anyway, the main thing that I got from that was, you know, Tom was very much in the

00:30:47.520 --> 00:30:55.440
[Guest]: mold of Gary and allowed me to kind of think in ways that I hadn't about data. So connecting

00:30:55.440 --> 00:30:59.680
[Guest]: a lot of the work that Gary was doing with the work that Jim was doing. And I decided

00:30:59.680 --> 00:31:05.000
[Guest]: I wanted to work with this person more. So we didn't initially work on epidemics. I got

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:10.040
[Guest]: to that a little bit later, but we did work on, you know, another very interesting aspect,

00:31:10.040 --> 00:31:14.360
[Guest]: which is the idea of nonprofits. And this also started moving me towards health because

00:31:14.360 --> 00:31:20.240
[Guest]: in the United States, about 60% of hospitals are nonprofit. More, I think, if you do it

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:28.600
[Guest]: by bed. But so we started thinking about why are some firms nonprofit, some firms for profit?

00:31:28.600 --> 00:31:34.240
[Guest]: And why do firms decide to, you know, sometimes choose each of these two different forms?

00:31:34.240 --> 00:31:40.240
[Guest]: Why do markets tolerate it in equilibrium? And why does it only happen in certain sectors

00:31:40.240 --> 00:31:43.520
[Guest]: and not in other sectors? So we started thinking about that. And again, that got me thinking

00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:49.000
[Guest]: more about health. And ultimately, when I was writing my dissertation, I think I was

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:54.720
[Guest]: able to put, you know, three of these influences all together in a way that's very, I'd like

00:31:54.720 --> 00:32:00.760
[Guest]: to think very Becker-esque. So I started just like many grad students at Chicago, I went

00:32:00.760 --> 00:32:05.040
[Guest]: through many topics, and each of them were actually fine. So I had my first topic was

00:32:05.040 --> 00:32:08.880
[Guest]: on how judges behave. The second topic was actually on whether or not this is the law

00:32:08.880 --> 00:32:13.160
[Guest]: influence, whether or not the felony murder rule, which we can dive into if you want to,

00:32:13.160 --> 00:32:17.040
[Guest]: but it's a very peculiar rule that says that if you, if somebody dies, while you're committing

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:20.800
[Guest]: a felony, you're liable for murder, even if you didn't intend it, whether or not that

00:32:20.800 --> 00:32:25.120
[Guest]: rule actually works and deterred, it actually has very complex effects. And so that was

00:32:25.120 --> 00:32:29.820
[Guest]: the second paper. But I rejected each of these papers. And the reason is because the standard

00:32:29.820 --> 00:32:33.280
[Guest]: at Chicago was, are you going to write the thing that that is not only going to be published

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:37.480
[Guest]: in a top three or top five journal, but that's really going to, you know, kind of put you

00:32:37.480 --> 00:32:42.280
[Guest]: on the map and put you on a track towards winning a big prize at the end of your career.

00:32:42.280 --> 00:32:47.360
[Guest]: And I didn't think either of those were that big, but then as soon as I was done clerking

00:32:47.360 --> 00:32:52.160
[Guest]: and was turning back to finishing my dissertation, I decided to dump all that because I had this

00:32:52.160 --> 00:32:59.160
[Guest]: idea one day as I was driving to the airport, which is to think about clinical trials. I

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:01.760
[Guest]: was thinking about clinical trials. I don't know why I was thinking about clinical trials,

00:33:01.760 --> 00:33:08.240
[Guest]: but I had this thought. I found it interesting that some clinical trials treated more people

00:33:08.240 --> 00:33:12.560
[Guest]: than other clinical trials. That is to say, some clinical trials, you know, you look at

00:33:12.560 --> 00:33:16.080
[Guest]: one treatment and you put half the people in control and half the people in that one

00:33:16.080 --> 00:33:20.440
[Guest]: treatment. And then other trials, you'd have two treatments you're looking at and a control

00:33:20.440 --> 00:33:26.120
[Guest]: and you do one third in each. And I thought, well, that's really interesting because especially

00:33:26.120 --> 00:33:30.360
[Guest]: if it's a blinded trial, you know, you're going to have this differences. You're going

00:33:30.360 --> 00:33:33.960
[Guest]: to get the same treatment maybe if they're common treatments across the two trials, you're

00:33:33.960 --> 00:33:38.520
[Guest]: going to have different beliefs about it. And then it occurred to me that there's this

00:33:38.520 --> 00:33:44.600
[Guest]: concept I had read out about called the placebo effect, where your expectations about a drug

00:33:44.600 --> 00:33:50.040
[Guest]: affect the outcomes that you have after consuming that drug. And this is just because I was

00:33:50.040 --> 00:33:54.280
[Guest]: doing background research with Thomas on data markets, learning how clinical trials work.

00:33:54.280 --> 00:33:58.720
[Guest]: And it occurred to me that this is a really interesting opportunity to study placebo effects.

00:33:58.720 --> 00:34:05.440
[Guest]: So I wrote a paper very quickly on how you can compare outcomes across two trials that

00:34:05.440 --> 00:34:11.800
[Guest]: are looking at at least one common treatment, but that have different allocations of patients

00:34:11.800 --> 00:34:16.240
[Guest]: to treatment. So different fractions getting treated to test for placebo effects. I immediately

00:34:16.240 --> 00:34:21.720
[Guest]: called up Thomas as soon as I stopped. This was, you know, probably like an hour drive

00:34:21.720 --> 00:34:25.240
[Guest]: at the end. I called Thomas and said I had this idea. He immediately saw that it was

00:34:25.240 --> 00:34:30.640
[Guest]: a great idea. And he said, call Gary. So I called Gary and he said, yeah, that's a fantastic

00:34:30.640 --> 00:34:34.880
[Guest]: idea. You should write that paper. And so within three months, I wrote a dissertation

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:40.400
[Guest]: on placebo effects. And so I knew also that that was actually a significant paper because

00:34:40.400 --> 00:34:44.240
[Guest]: here are two people that thought not just it was an okay paper, but it was a really

00:34:44.240 --> 00:34:48.600
[Guest]: interesting paper. And so that's how I kind of locked it in for me that I cared about

00:34:48.600 --> 00:34:55.200
[Guest]: health economics, which is, you know, I had the data market stuff. I had now this dissertation.

00:34:55.200 --> 00:34:58.520
[Guest]: So health economics was going to be an area I thought was going to be very interesting.

00:34:58.520 --> 00:35:03.240
[Amit Varma]: And so that's how I ended up back at health. And that's a good time to take a quick commercial

00:35:03.240 --> 00:35:07.480
[Amit Varma]: break. We'll come back after the break and, you know, get up to speed with bringing you

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:12.480
[Amit Varma]: to the current COVID crisis. And then we'll talk about that in some detail. We'll be back

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:19.240
[Amit Varma]: in a minute. Okay. If you're listening to the scene in the unseen, it means you like

00:35:19.240 --> 00:35:23.920
[Amit Varma]: listening to audio and you're thirsty for knowledge. That being the case, I'd urge you

00:35:23.920 --> 00:35:29.160
[Amit Varma]: to check out Storytel, the sponsors of this episode. Storytel is an audio book platform

00:35:29.160 --> 00:35:33.760
[Amit Varma]: that has a massive range of audio books from around the world. The international collection

